{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558881/1946021701/0640.xml":{"full_text":"EPI L CHANGES\nSEEN IN BANKING\njBanks Enter Sales Field\nThrough Establishment\nCredit, Loan Groups\nBT WILLIAM R. KUHNS\nTil# art of selling bank service\n1# aomething that banks have been\nthinking hard about these past few\nyears, particularly during the war.\nThere hav# long been signs of an\nepochal transition in banking\nthought but during the war sever\nal special factors operated to spur\nthe banker\u2019s sense of merchandis\ning and his inclination to go out\nafter buainess. Some banks had al\nways had sales programs but cer\ntainly salesmanship has never\nbeen an outstanding characteriztic\nof the profession.\nJust what the change will mean\nto the bank-using public and the\nnature of business might be\njudged better If we examine quick\nly some specific things taking\npjac*.\nIn order to assure and facilitate\nj credit to small business the banks\nof more than 40 communities have\n.formed local credit groups with\ntotal assets in excess of $500,000,\n000. Their purpose is to provide\nassurance through cooperative ac\ntion that every competent indi\nvidual desiring a loan should be\nable to get it, together with help\nand counsel.\nIn the real estate field, banks\nare taking the lead in many lo\ncalities toward organizing home\nplanning groups which meet regu\nlarly to learn end save regularly\nto buy.\nAs consumer goods Degin to\ntome back to the market in quan\ntities, more than 10,000 banks are\nready to provide purchasers with\nconsumer credit services. Plans\n\u2022re well along toward setting up\nseveral regional groups of Hanks\nwhich will then be in a position\nto offer industry whatever ad\nvantages derive from a uniform\nplan of consumer credit extending\nover a wide area.\nThe loan program of GI legis\nlation is the latest and perhaps the\ngreatest challenge to banks to\ngrow out of the war. Many veter\nans naturally regard the loan\nprivilege as a bonus. Also many\npersons with something to sell,\nlike a small business of uncertain\nlife or an over-priced farm, eye\nthe veteran\u2019s right to borrow as\na means of unloading. The banks\nare evolving a program to meet\nthis challenge, and the basis of the\npl\u00abB is an attitude of friendly help\nfulness to the veteran as an in-'\ndividual, not as a problem, andj\nclose cooperation with th* Veter-1\nans Bureau.\nBUolJNlfiOO AliVIDH oo x\nSERVICE NEWS WAREHOUSE\n\nWorkmen are shown as they worked on the curving roof of the Service News warehouse on S.\n16th street. The handsome new building will serve as a storage warehouse and main distribution point\nfor magazines, newspapers and other publications handled by the Service News company. _\nPublic Housing Construction\nSets High Industrial Target\n5,499 Housing Units Built;\nAn Average Four Per\nDay For Three Years\n__ t\nThere are 5,499 public housing !i\nunits in Wilmington today and. 1\nthey were constructed at a pace 1\nwhich local business leaders hope\nwill be equalled by an upsurge in\nindustrial activity here in the fu\nture.\nThe reason an average of more\nthan four dwellings per day were\nconstructed in Wilmington between\nMay 1, 1940, and November, 1943,\nis that the population of the city\nincreased more in 1942 than it had\nin the previous 200 years.\nAs one Wilmington native said, j\nglancing at the p a c d city\nstreets, \"Times have changed. In\n1938 you could shoot a shotgun\ndown the middle of Front street\nwithout hitting anybody.\u201d\nHousing was one phase of in\ndustrial life in Wilmington that\nkept pace with the increasing pop\nulation\u2014a population with money\nto spend. It was a fast pace. So\nfast, in fact, that Wilmington,\ndemonstrating a rare perceptive\nness of vv..dt the future held,\nformed the first local housing au\nthority in North Carolina In 1938.\nWhile the war, with its cry for\nspeed\u2014speed\u2014speed.', gave impe\ntus to the construction of housing\naere, the story is worth recount\ning:\nJ\u2014ij me uic j toi iPTt/, a\nBy the end of the year 1943, a\ntotal of $15,908,100 had been ex-\npended on low-rent and war hous- i\ning projects. There were 5,499 1\ndwellings constructed at an over- i\n11 average cost of $2,893 per\n.welling.\nFirst two projects undertaken by\nbe local housing authority were\nor low-income groups. By No\n\u25a0ember 16, 1940, 216 two-story,\nirick apartments, for whites, were\nully occupied in Nesbitt Courts,\nin the south end of Front street,\nind 246 similar units called Tay\nor Homes, located at the end of\n>Jorth Fifth street, were complete\ny filled by Negro tenants,\nincome Limit.!\nNo family may move into Nes\noitt Courts if the income is greater\nhan $1,620 yearly; at Taylor\nSomes the maximum income for\nidmission is $1,260 yearly. During\n:944, 94 families left the two proj\nects because of excessive incomes,\nmere are eight rent grades, rang\nng in price from $12 to $33 per\nnonth.\nBefore the first Liberty ship, the\nlebulon B. Vance, slid down the\nvays of the North Carolina Ship\nsuilding company on Dec. 6, 1941,\nVilmington had 1,737 public hous\nng dwellings. A scant 24 hours\nater America was at war, and\nhe local housing authority geared\nts plans to produce four times the\nbanned housing for the city.\nThe nine ways of the shipyard\njecame increasingly busy, and in\n943 shipyard employment reached\ni peak of 20,800 persons. To ac\n:ommoaate the shipyard workers\nmd servicemen stationed at near.\n)y military installations, 3,762\nnore housing units were built in\n942 and 1943.\nIn quick succession, war hous\nng projects sprang up in Lake\nforest, Hillcrest and Maffitt Vil\nage. There were masonry dwell\nngs for two and four families,\njrefabricated demountable houses\no r shipyard workers, temporary\niormitories, and furnished war\napartments made of gypsum\naoard construction.\nTemporary Housing\nMaffitt Village was designed\nalong sti'ictly temporary lines in\n:ost, construction and liability.\nAverage overall cost of each vil\nlage unit was $2,566\u2014a figure\nwhich includes land, grading, utili\nties and overhead, all of the\nfactors which are considered in\nthe construction of a dwelling.\nRents range from $20 for one-bed\nroom apartments to $34 for three\nbedrooms.\nLake Forest masonry apart\nments cost from $35.50 to $40.50,\ndepending upon size. Hillcrest, the\nNegro development, has rents\nfrom $22 to $26.\nGrand total of rentals collected\nin 1944 on war and low rent hous\ning was $1,814,475.82 and the fed\neral government subsidy on the\nlow rent units in that yeai\namounted to $5.52 monthly foi\neach dwelling\u2014only 49 percent oi\nthe maximum subsidy of $62,172.5C\navailable In year, because in\ncreased incomes allowed tenant!\nto pay higher rents. Rentals are\ngauged so that they equal roughlj\n20 per cent of a tenant\u2019s Income,\nContributions\nWilmington and New Hanovei\ncounty make their contributions tc\nthe housing projects in the form\nof tax-exemptions; exemption:\nwhich help hold the rent withir\nthe range of low-income groups.\nUnlike other tax-exempt groups\u2014\nschools, churches, fire stations\u2014\nthe local housing authority makes\nlump sum payments to the city\nand county in lieu of taxes on the\ntwo low rent developments and the\nfigure has climbed until m 1944 t\nreached $6,311 and m 1945 $7 876.\nThe city and county also receive\npayments in lieu of taxes on toe\nwar housing development In 1944\nthe payments were $86,374 and in\n1945, $84,375.\nAlthough the end of the war has\nbrought about a lessening of the\ntotal number of workers in Wil\nmington, the local housing authori\nty already is taking steps to con\nsolidate its wartime gains for the\ngood of the city\u2019s future.\nRecently in the Wilmington City\nhall representatives of toe Nation\nal Housing agency, Federal Public\nHousing Authority and the Federal\nHousing Administration met with\nlocal housing people and members\nof city-county Advisory board to\ndecide the fate of the public war\nhousing units here.\nThe following recommendations\nwere made by toe housing authori\nty:\nAll of Maffitt Village, except 800\ndemountable units, be declared\ntemporary and demolished and\ncarted away. This applies to 2,962\nunits:\nRemainder of public war hous\ning be declared permanent and\ndisposed of as follows:\nA. The 216 units for Negroes at\nHillcrest be sold to toe Wilming\nton Housing Authority.\nB. The 584 masonry units at\nLake Forest be left in place and\nsold to private owners.\nC. The 800 demountable units at\nMaffitt Village and the 475 at Lake\nForest be retained on their present\nsites, if a postwar demand exists\nfor them and that, if retained,\nUlCjr auiu ynvaic uwuu a.\nOther Recommendations\nIt was also recommended that\nseveral buildings in Maffitt Vil\nlage, including the commercial\nbuilding on the Carolina Beach\nhighway, the Raleigh community\nbuilding, and perhaps three of the\nmasonry dormitory buildings be\nconverted to post-war industrial\nuse and sold to private owners.\nFederal housing officials at the\nmeeting said the recommenda\ntions of local committees was the\ngoverning factor in governmental\ndecisions regarding public hous\ning.\nH. R. Emory is secretary and\nexecutive director of the local\nhousing authority.\nServing with Emory on the ex\necutive staff are:\nB. H. Marshall, Jr., C. C. Chat\nham, Jr., Mittie H. Fuller, Roger\nHelms, E. William Burnett, J. W.\nGrant, H. Carl Moultrie, Arthur\nH. Glazier, O. T. Faison, Carl E.\nSonderman and William B. Camp\nbell, attorney.\nCommissioners of the authority,\nwho serve without pay, are Harry\nM. Solomon, chairman; R. Stew\nart, the Rev. Walter B. Freed, C.\nGay and Fred E. Little.\nMembers of the Advisory board,\nheaded by E. L. White as perma\nnent chairman, will be charged\nwith the responsibility for making\nplans for the future disposal and\nmanagement of the war housing\nunits here. They have announced\nthat they will visit and personally\ninspect all local war housing be\nfore making specific recommen\naations.\nPublic housing In Wilmington\nhas gone a long way toward bopst\ning the city to its present high\nstatus in industrial activity, and\npointing the .way to realization of\ntile industrial and economic po\ntential here. That there are still\nslums in Wilmington cannot be de\nnied. Neither can it be denied\nthat, with the heightening of the\ntempo of port activity plus the es\ntablishing of new industries, Wil\nmington is about to embark' upon\nan era of expansion which will ful.\nly justify the name given the port\nwas connection with the Quota\nin 1732.\nTlie name was \u201cNew Town.\" 1\nKfclUWVfcKSlUIN IS\nNOT TOO FAR OFF\nRush For Consumer Goods\nNo Fair Indications Of\nProgress Thus Far\nBy CORNELIUS F. MOYNIHAN,\nCambridge Associates\nReconversion is a lot farther\nalong than the scramble for avail\nable consumer goods would indi\ncate.\nA good many, not all, of the\nmajor obstacles to complete recon\nversion will be overcome within\nthe next six months. Some may\nremain for a year or more, Short\nage of key raw materials and skill\ned manpower is the chief bar, dis\nregarding wage and price factors,\nto immediate solution of reconver\nsion problems by industry general\nly.\nStabilization\nBefore V-J Day, however, the\nexperts were estimating a drop of\n80 points in the Federal Reserve\nindex of industrial production. The\nactual decrease between July and\nOctober was only 46 points. Recent\nfigures s u g gest stabilization\naround the October level during\nthe transition period and a range\nof 160 to 180 for 1946. The base\n100 is the 1935-39 average.\nComplete reconversion is depen\ndent upon the availability of raw\nmaterials,- length of time taken to\ninstall peacetime processes of\nmanufacture, and period neces\nsary to re-adapt labor to peace\ntime labor schedules. The peak of\npost-war layoffs in defense indus\ntries was reached in the two\nmonths following V-J Day.\nBuilding\nAccording to figures released by\nthe War Production Board late in\nOctober. thg Raiding indusery has j<\nat hand materials such as cement,\nready mixed concrete, stone, and\ngravel while asphalt products, clay\nand structural insulation board\nwere given a lag of eight to ten\nweeks. According to early WPB es\ntimates the supply situation would\napproach normal in the Spring of\n1946 but this may have moved for\nward now.\nTextiles\nIn the automotive industry, the\npresent labor situation seems tc\nbe the chief bottleneck. Most of\nthe automobile manufacturers are\nutilizing the same dies and styles\nfor 1946 model cars as were used\nfor the 1942 models with a few\nchanges. Really new models will\nprobably not be on the market be\nfore 1948. An excellent reconver\nsion comparison in the automotive\nis the famous shift by Ford from\nModel T. to Model A passenger\ncars in the late twenties. From the\nlast Model T. to full production on\nModel A required 18 months.\nInvention\nNew inventions and new methods\nof manufacture since that time\nhave speeded up this process\nsomewhat, but the same principal\nobstacles must be overco\nindustries manufacture' \u201er *'!i\nmass production scale\nA factor stimulating Qu\nconversion is the many r\u2019 .'VI\nwhich have sprung up durin eS\nwar years that can be co^r-!\nto peacetime production nf d\nhold appliances. Numerous 'S!'\nborn corporations plan to sten\nmass production of these 0\nsoon as possible in order' .V s'\na foothold in a highly cn^ \u2018!l\niieia. m\nBuying Incom* I\nThe Nation\u2019s effective buv-- 1\ncome figure will be well' ar. 1\nlast year. Increased employ* l' f\nm the early part of the vea;- y 4\nincreased payments the last hai> I\nof the year to members of 'he I\ned forces within the countryT I\nstead of abroad were enough 1\ncounteract losses due to unemViov\u2019 1\nment and strikes. r' I\nRetail sales on a country y\nbasis will rise to a new ali.titr!\npeak for 1915. Department of Con I\nmerce estimates put the total\n$73,500,000,000.\nWe are finished with fhe fiw\nphase of post-war reconversion\nand it hasn\u2019t ben too hard to take\"\nA recent survey proved that 711\npercent housewives prefer to shon\nfor all their needs In one *torc.\nTo remove ink stain from cotton\nand linens apply hydrosulphiy\ndinse, then apply oxalic acid. 1\nNEW MOTOR COMPANY\u2019S HOME 1\nThis partially completed building, at S. 11th and Market streets,\nwill be the home of the Cape Fear Motor company when it is com\npleted in fhe near future. The building will be of modern design,\ninside and out, and will enhance the beauty of Market street, which\nstreet it faces.\nS' 1\nWe Take Special Pride In Our\nAll Work Guaranteed\nI -PHONE 439 5\nSMITH\u2019S SHOE REPAIR\n127 PRINCESS STREET\nt\nJO\u2019S CLUB I\nWilmington's Most Popular Night Spot... i\nDANCING NIGHTLY\nDELIGHTFUL ENTERTAINMENT\nCHOICE FOODS\nI PLENTY OF BEER I\nI CHOICE WINES i\nand\nSTEAKS SEA FOODS 1\n1 CHICKEN-IN-THE-ROUOH\nJO\u2019S CLUB BAND\nPlaying Every Saturday Night\n\nCOME IN TONIGHT AND EVERT NIGHT\nDIAL 7301 FOR RESERVATIONS\nJO\u2019S CLUB\n\nJ. K. (BILL) DAVIS, Owner\n3j/2 Miles Out on Carolina Beach Road\n_","height":"27552","width":"20604"}}
